      "text": "Chapter 3. Things Forgotten\nColorado Springs, CO, 1987\nRoyce Lockwood sat with his head in his hands, alone in the huge hanger. It was over. The worst had actually happened and what could they do now? The side effects of the device had been too much for Christopher to bear and now how could he face what he had done? They can never know. He thought to himself. I must hide this. Hide it from my family, hide it from everyone. He looked around at the room full of equipment. The machine had been destroyed, and now it was all gone. The lab was a mess, and the equipment was scattered everywhere. Everything was covered in dust, and there was a smell in the air of burnt wires and chemicals.\n\"How could this have happened?\" Royce asked no one in particular. His voice echoed through the empty hanger in between sobs. He only cried like this when he knew he was alone. But right now it was happening regardless of who came in that closed door.\nHe walked slowly around the room, trying to put things back where they belonged. It was of no use, things were scattered like wreckage from a tornado. The electrical blast had all but destroyed the supercapacitor and he could see exposed wiring within the spectral generator. How was he to replace these parts? They were priceless, and all his wealth had been dedicated to this one effort.\nThe one thing that remained as it had been was the flux chamber. It was sitting on the ground with a large dent in the center of it. The gearbox was cracked and its contents were scattered around the room. He reached down and picked up one of the spheres. It glowed briefly and then began to fade. What was he going to do? It was now in Christopher's hands entirely. The fate of the world in fact, and this was no exaggeration. This was the key to everything.\n\"I'm so sorry Chris,\" Royce said as he watched the last energy dissipate into the air. \"You know we didn't mean to hurt anyone. Last of all you my friend. Last of all you.\"\nIn a fit of anger, he threw a wrench from the toolkit to his left as hard as he could, and the little missile smashed into a mini-fridge across the thirty-foot room and put a dent in the upper door, breaking the thin white handle. He began beating the drywall with his bare fists and screaming in sorrow. Each punch hurt, but it felt well-deserved. Finally, holes in the wall and hoarse from yelling in the dry bunker air, He closed his eyes and tried to forget that room. Tried to forget those dreams and what they had been so close to achieving. Shaking his head, he said, \"Good luck my friend,\" and his face went expressionless as he locked the door to the cellar behind him.\n",
