      "text": "Chapter Four: Through the Fire\nLockwood Family Estate, Colorado Springs, Two Months After Disappearance Day, 1987\n     Aston had always appreciated the way rain sounded on glass. Settled comfortably in his Father’s Green Leather chair, a cup of tea in his hands, he stared pensively out the windows of the study across the expanse of lawn to the front gate. The steady throb of another party in the next room could be heard through the thick mahogany paneling and, with it, the distant tune of a Christmas Carol. Something about the sound was unnerving to Aston and it brought to his mind to many memories of the recent tragedy. The Lockwood family Estate sprawled across the majority of twenty acres and was at this moment lit up in nearly every window. It wasn’t Christmas Day yet, but the Lockwoods had hosted this party early to accommodate some of the schedules of the wealthiest socialites. It was events like these that brought in the big donations to the Lockwood Family Charity. Headlights lit up the misty dusk scene outside, and Aston watched as a beautiful sports car pulled up. The owner stepped out into the rain and a black umbrella expanded to cover his expensive suit while the eager valet boy ran to the far side of the car to assist the lady with her door. Aston observed as the couple shared the umbrella and exchanged hurried and grateful greetings with the Valet before heading inside the warmly lit front doors.  adding a strangely comforting aura to the serene atmosphere. The gentle howl of the wind and patter of rain on the windows elegantly framed the night scenery. \n            A log in the fireplace cracked loudly, and Aston jumped. The cup in his hand slipped and smashed against the hardwood floor. Having been startled from his comfortable trance, he exclaimed in annoyance and decided to let the maid clean up the glass. He stood and stretched, yawning loudly. He knew that they would be waiting for him in the loud room beyond the study door and did not much want to participate in his parent’s publicity stunts. He had writing to do. It wasn’t that he didn’t like parties; they just bored him. When everyone knows your name, it takes some of the fun of anonymity out of the whole experience. He wished that just once he could sit in the corner of the room and be unseen. As he thought this he found his gaze drawn to the magnificent portrait hanging over the ornate fireplace mantle. His Ancestor, Sigmund Lockwood, the original founder of the Lockwood Foundation, stared down with the confident stoicism that only a painting can possess. He had always wanted to be like the man but had never actually met him. Well, that wasn’t necessarily true, as he had held Aston the day he was born. But that could hardly count as meeting someone, could it? The flash of lightning out the floor-to-ceiling windows lit the room up for a moment and threw Aston’s shadow against the wall. He turned towards the towering bookshelves, filled to overflowing with classic books, memoirs, and untouched volumes that had gathered the dust of several centuries. Of all the Lockwoods, Sigmund was by far the best read, and, glancing back at the portrait, Aston smiled. In typical Lockwood fashion he had requested his portrait in the Library. He was shown leaning on several books stacked spine-out, worn with age. They were the most colorful parts of the portrait and were meant to send a message. This man was a reader. Aston leaned close to the painting, enjoying for a moment, the warmth of the fire. The three books were staggered, but their titles could clearly be made out. The Origin of the Human System, Beyond the Looking Glass by Lewis Carrol, and The Universal Opposite. He had read Carrol’s book, but the others were unfamiliar to him. Personally, he had found Beyond the Looking Glass to be somewhat uninspired, and he wondered what Sigmund saw in the book that he so loved. He had read it a long time ago and found it quite boring. A sudden shift in the wind, or perhaps someone falling down in the next room, caused the flame to jump. He wanted to search the bookshelf to see if the two unknown books were there. His curiosity had peaked. The now dimly lit room was insufficient and due to the family’s decision not to install electric lighting in the ancient room, he made to stoke the fire. He lifted a log and tossed it on the small black grate covered in coals. Taking the poker, he squatted and began poking the coals to coax the flame back into being. He continued stabbing into the ashes and looked longingly towards the shelf. That must have been the reason that he accidentally pressed his knee rather firmly on the hearth, and the hard marble caused him to wince in pain. As he recoiled from the hurt knee, the poker violently stabbed the back of the fireplace. Now, what Aston expected to hear was the thud of iron on marble. Instead, he heard a hollow thump followed by a click somewhere up in the wall behind his Uncle’s Portrait. The band in the next room picked up the tempo, but Aston hardly noticed. A few moments passed as he contemplated what had just happened. Then in a moment so sudden, the fire was gone. The dark room became a tomb punctuated with muffled music. Then he heard it. A whirring sound and from somewhere beyond the fireplace, a sliver of light appeared, and the marble backing began to open like a door.",
