      "text": "The ballroom was lit up like New York on Christmas Eve and in the dappled light that filtered through the stain glass window he saw her. It was that time of the afternoon that shrouds its visitors in golden haze. He felt the haze. However, it had nothing to do with the time. In fact, he had things that needed to be done and places to be. None of that mattered. Her. The woman. The perfect image of a woman. He stood for a moment lost in thought, mesmerized by her. She was in a simple light blue dress with a white cardigan and scarf. A little under-dressed for the gala but that was what drew his attention the most. She seemed to him to move in slow motion. A gentle smile crossed her slender face and his own unconsciously smiled as well. She just had that kind of face, was it her face? What was so magical about this woman? Then without a moment’s pause he began descending the small staircase to the main level. The room was packed with wealthy guests and famous faces. He barely noticed the stout form of Leslie Graves who was in a heated discussion with someone he would have recognized if he had tried. But the woman. As he pressed through the mob of millionaires and shiny suits he could see her making her way towards a table against the far wall. Then, and it happened completely by accident, she caught his gaze. Just for a moment, they locked eyes, and his heart leaped into his throat like he was a schoolboy again. He was both amused and terrified by this. He saw something change in her eyes, some common curiosity, or was it familiarity? As he walked towards her, slowly nodding politely to the other guests as he passed. Don’t hurry. They were closer, so close. Then within mere moments of the first time, he had seen the mysterious Lillian Aster they were closer than he had ever felt with anyone. I couldn’t help but come and say hello. He started, feeling a touch awkward at how directly he had made his approach. I’m glad you did, saved me the trouble of getting your attention myself. She smiled, and he noticed that she had dimples. He laughed and asked would you like a drink ma’am? Without hesitation, she said she would love one but she had given up alcohol long ago and vowed to never touch it again. What a woman he thought and they sat down together at a mahogany table under the smallest crystal chandelier he had ever seen. The glimmer in her eyes was, to him, deeper in hue than the rainbows thrown around the wallpapered walls from the light above. What is your name? He asked, his eyes never leaving hers. “It’s Lillian,” she replied with just the slightest hesitation, “what’s yours?”. He smiled and noticed that her eyes were the most captivating shade of green he had ever… wait. He paused in confusion. \n“What’s yours?” echoed back in his mind. What’s yours? My what?... wait. He felt something. Somewhere deep inside, a tiny tingle in the legs that turned them numb and an ache in the back of his neck. It was panic.\n“What’s yours??” He seemed to see the room begin to ripple and she, her… The woman… Lillian slowly faded to black.\n\n",
