      "text": "Something made him stir… maybe it was how the bright sun slipped through the crack between his eyelids or maybe it was how cold the earth was beneath him. Regardless, he awoke and stretched, yawning loudly into the morning air. For a moment he sat motionless, his eyes closed just listening. The glen felt joyful and new somehow. Like yesterday’s rain had left behind it a small piece of the heaven from which it fell. Joy like rain. Tweet Tweet Ckurrr ckuurrrr went the little bird far above him somewhere in the upper limbs of the tall oak.\n \nChristopher awoke with a start. The dark room was as black as night. He momentarily clutched at his chest in panic but the faithful metal of the key and chain reassured him. Then like a wave he remembered. A wave of deep black nothing. It was a Thursday. Like any other Thursday in his life except for one detail. Her. He touched his knees softly as if they were still bruised, and tears began to flow down his cheeks. Silent sobs turned into deep gasping cries and he held his head like a little boy and rocked. Just rocked until he couldn’t feel. A destination that never came. He would always feel. He would always hurt. He realized that it wasn’t a key he had so suddenly reached for. It was a ring. His ring. The pain was indescribable. It was him. In him. Around Him. The hopes that had filled his future were only distant memories of what could never be. It was on a Thursday, that terrible day, when he had zipped the last zipper on the last of her bags and for the last time made sure her car was full of gas. The moments that he lived, they lived, we lived were dead moments. When crying doesn’t help, when begging has no end, when logic yields no result. The death of a life is the worst thing he thought grimly. I will always love you Christopher. She had said, what did that even mean? It had to be meaningless. Logically that made no sense but there it was. Death with a velvet bow. A final torturous kiss. The simple lies that keep the dream alive. He looked around the room and noticed a little boy in the doorway. His baby blue footie pajamas, adorned with stars, were a stark contrast to the black doorway beyond the hall and he seemed to shine. Aston held his breath and asked a question that was hidden somewhere inside a locked box in his mind. James? Baby boy, is that you? The little boy didn’t answer and instead he just slowly faded away until all that was left was the imprint his little feet had left on the carpet. Aston didn’t know why he wasn’t scared. He knew that anyone else would, and should, feel terrified by what he had just seen. They just didn’t understand. In a strange way it was comfort. To him it was peace. He smiled and reached to pull the chain on the bedside lamp. Cththrk. The little room was bathed in the golden light that man so prizes and he pivoted, slipping his feet into the house shoes on the floor. That was one thing that he liked about her memory. Houseshoes. He pushed that out of his head. What time is it? He wondered sleepily and turned the bedside clock towards him. He turned it away every night because the light would keep him awake and it bothered him to see green through his eyelids. 08:14 AM. Read the little led display. He groaned and fell back into bed for a moment. Thursday. He really had to get up. There was a lot to do and he had yet to decipher the message. It would be best to get that done. He had time but not much of it. With a final sigh he slid out of bed and began dressing for the day.",
