      "text": "Ellis Island, 1884\n    The young twenty-eight-year-old genius stared at the land in the distance that would within two years be the resting place of an American Icon. Ellis island, just a processing center for immigration into mainland America, was the next stop on his long journey and he was anxious to be onland. The ship had taken on some water and, had there been no sump pump, would surely have been more of a burden; however, the day had been saved. The young genius had saved the day the young genius named Nikola Tesla. He turned to see a young woman leaning on the rail, she appeared to be irish or perhaps welsh. Not an unattractive woman he thought to himself. She was soon joined by a father and two brothers which caused Nikola’s attention to waver, but only slightly. It was the logistics of the thing more than the principle. He turned back to the land in the distance. It was said to be a land of opportunity, and coming from his austrian background, he could see the promise. There was wealth and the chance to change things. He longed to strike out and make a name for himself without the stigma of having not attended college. He made his way to the back of the boat to see the things the others were missing. While they looked forwards he pensively looked back for a moment to take it in. The ocean empty behind them and only land ahead. \n    Upon disembarking Tesla was immediately met by Charles Rasterson, an associate of the famous Thomas Edison who eagerly welcomed him to the country and to New York. “Good trip?” Asked the man. He wasn’t much for idle dialogue and Tesla was eager to oblige. \n",
