      "text": "Arthur let the memory take him back. Back to the year when it all began, 1879. Professor Bell was by far one of the most distinguished men in all of Europe, of that Doyle was quite certain. The oddity was that he was also one of the most selfish. He was an enigma. A cowboy of sorts like he belonged in a separate time. His eyes were of a deep hazel green. Piercing eyes that were somehow gentle at the same time. As if they were as meek as a lamb yet as sharp as daggers with the secrets of a thousand suns and two planets at rest between them. He was a career-long bachelor and unlike many of his time he seemed to be okay with that. Their sadly short tenure as partners in this secret plan began on that first day on the coast and had ended in Switzerland on a cold winter day. He had seen something that day that he saw every night before bed. He saw it as if it were tattooed on the back of his eyelids. Two men locked in a vicious struggle atop a cliff. The roaring waves and pounding boom of the falls and the spray of water on his face. If he had only gone up the left-hand path he would have been in time. Surely he could have been in time. But time had run out. He could never admit what he had seen. Truth be told he barely knew what it was. One moment Bell and his assailant were wrestling and punching each other. It looked like Bell had the upper hand but Arthur wondered if he only told himself that in order to feel better. They were fighting over a small metal object slightly larger than the size of a cuban cigar with an oblong end shaped like a taurus. Doyle remembered shouting up to him in anger and gesticulating frantically and uselessly to stop the man from pushing his friend over the precipice. But then, and it happened in a moment, a flash of brilliant green light sparked into the air like lightning and the two men fell apart in surprise. The small piece of metal hovered in the air between them and began to glow. It got brighter and brighter, so very bright. The light hurt. It stung like something out of a dream. The prickling of his skin made the hair stand up on end. Doyle had seen Bell turn towards him as if in a moment of recognition, some moment of intellect, and light so bright it cast shade cut the scene in tatters. Doyle could remember only pieces from there. A strong pulse in the air that reminded him of a beach before a storm, and the cracking sound of a horse-whip. He was knocked to the ground by an unseen force and the world went mercifully dark.\n",
