      "text": "John Pierpont Morgan Jr. (September 7, 1867 – March 13, 1943) was an American banker, finance executive, and philanthropist. He inherited the family fortune and took over the business interests including J.P. Morgan & Co. after his father J. P. Morgan died in 1913.\nAfter graduating from St. Paul's School and Harvard College, Morgan trained as a finance executive working for his father and grandfather. He became a banking financier, a lending leader, and a director of several companies. He supported New York's Society for the Lying-In Hospital, the Red Cross, the Episcopal Church, and endowed the creation of a rare book and manuscript collection at the Morgan Library.\nMorgan brokered a deal that positioned his company as the sole munitions and supplies purchaser during World War I for the British and French governments, bringing his company a 1% commission on $3 billion ($30 million). He was also a banking broker for financing to foreign governments both during and after the war.\n\n125 London Wall,20th Century Press Archives,245 Park Avenue,25 Bank Street,270 Park Avenue (1960–2021),270 Park Avenue (2021–present),277 Park Avenue,28 Liberty Street,383 Madison Avenue,Aetna Life and Casualty,Allies of World War I,American Fletcher Corporation,American Savings and Loan,Anglo-French Financial Commission,Anne Morgan (philanthropist),Banca Commerciale Italiana Trust Co.,Bank One Corporation,Bank United of Texas,Bath Iron Works,Beacon Rail,Bear Stearns,Belle da Costa Greene,Blythe Masters,Board of directors,Boca Grande, Florida,Bookbinding,Cecil Spring Rice,Cedar Hill Cemetery (Hartford, Connecticut),CenTrust Bank,Chairperson,Charles Francis Adams III,Chase (bank),Chase Bank,Chase Center,Chase Field,Chase Paymentech,Chase Tower (Amarillo),Chase Tower (Chicago),Chase Tower (Dallas),Chase Tower (El Paso),Chase Tower (Englewood, Colorado),Chase Tower (Indianapolis),Chase Tower (Milwaukee),Chase Tower (Oklahoma City),Chase Tower (Phoenix),Chase Tower (Rochester