      "text": "***\nChapter Eight - \"Yes, wonderful things.\"\n10:00 AM - 5 November 1922 - KV62, N.E. corner of the entrance to the tomb of Ramses VI, Valley of the Kings\nA very eager Howard carter was attacking the masonry with his practiced technique. It was warm but tolerable, a typical day in November. Very hot but excellent for the body. His physician would have been pleased with his physical condition. If he were there, at least. But doctors were far from his mind. He was desperate. Desperate to find something. It was roughly ten in the morning when he first encountered the entrance to the fated Tomb. Arthur Callender was the one who first shouted out. \n\"Carter! I see the top of a staircase!\"\nCarter almost felt giddy. Finally, something. There were to be sixteen steps on that staircase, and they carefully worked until the detritus and debris were safely removed from the area. Howard, with his suit and mustache, looked quite out of place against the hot sand. \"Now that the whole of the sealed doorway was laid bare various seal impressions bearing the cartouche of  Tût-ankh-Amen were discernible, more in particular in the lower portion of the plastering of the doorway where the impressions were clearest. In the upper part of this sealed doorway, traces of two distinct re-openings and successive re-closings disclosed were apparent, and that the sealed seal impressions first noticed on Nov. 5 of the Royal Necropolis - i.e., 'Anubis over Nine Foes', had been used for the re-closing. Here was evidence of at least the reign of the discovered tomb, but its true significance was still a puzzle, for, in the lower rubbish that filled the stair-case entrance, we found masses of broken potsherds and broken boxes, the latter bearing the names and protocol of Akhenaten, Smenkh-Ka-Ra, and Tut-ankh-Amen, and with what was even more upsetting a scarab of Tehutimes III, as well as a fragment bearing the cartouche of Amenhetep III. These conflicting data led us, for a time to believe that we were about to open a royal cache of the El Amarna branch of the XVIIIth Dyn. Monarchs, and that {the} from the evidence mentioned above it had been probably opened and used more than once.\" - Carter's Diary 24 Nov. 1922.\n***\n4:30 PM - 24 November 1922 - KV62, N.E. corner of the entrance to the tomb of Ramses VI, Valley of the Kings\nCallender had finally reached the first of the doorways to the tomb. As he reached out to touch the door, his hand shook slightly. Lord Carvanon stood atop the staircase, his tophat standing higher than seemed possible against the sky. He had a fever in his eyes. To his left stood Engelbach, a Chief inspector at the Antiquities Department; he had brought company with him this evening, and they were eager to see the excavation. But they seemed to be eager in a different manner. Carter didn't much like the man, or his photographer friend Harry Burton, as the first just seemed... off. The way they spoke was different from that of one given to his craft. Carter bounded down the stairs, being careful not to trip. \n\"We are here upon a mystery indeed,\" he murmured, looking closer at the stones.\nHis fingers traced the hieroglyphic characters on the lintel. They read \"Tutankhamun\", and below it, \"Horus\". The name meant \"crowned one\" or \"king crowned with glory\". The odd thing was that he would have sworn the doors to this tomb had been opened before. It certainly appeared... \n\"Carter, do you think this tomb has been opened before?\" Callender asked in a reverent quiet voice. He turned to the man and smiled. \n\"Callender my friend, you and I... you and I... \" he let this float off into the hot Egyptian air and turned back to the door. \n\"Well? Lord Carvanon barked from above in his deep voice, \"What of it, Carter?\" \n\"We should hold fast till tomorrow to make sure we are out of the heat of the day, but it looks good!\" he replied. \n\"It does indeed appear we are not the first to visit this burial. See here? This carving depicts Pharaoh Tutankhamun, with Horus the falcon god on his head, standing before Osiris, the lord of the dead.\"\nThe hole they were standing in was deep, and the stairs steep so the huddled group of men were crammed together at the door of the burial chamber.\n\"And see there?\" he pointed. \"A cartouche, carved in stone, depicting King Tut himself.\"\nThere was a sudden flurry of activity as the other diggers began moving in to see the drawing. Murmurs broke out like wildfire. \n***\n7:00 AM - 25 November 1922 - The Doorway to the tomb of Tût-ankh-Amen\nThey gathered at seven and pretended that they had actually slept that night. How could one sleep with such a mystery at hand?\nCarter scribbled in his notebook, \"Noted seals\". \n\"Okay! I think we can begin.\" He called up to Lord Carvanon.\nLord Carnarvon came forward, his hands clasped behind his back, and gazed down intently on the doorway. The light from his torch played across his features and illuminated his strong jawline. He was dressed in his usual garb, consisting of a linen shirt and breeches. He was eager to see what lay behind those stones.\nCarvanon moved to stand beside him. Both men stood quietly, gazing down at the door, their faces reflecting the awe and excitement of the moment. There was a slight breeze blowing around them, carrying away the dust stirred up during the last few days' excavations. The seals of Tût-ankh-Amen and the Royal Necropolis stared back at them from the stone door. It took a huge effort from Callendar and Carter, along with the other excavators, to move the stone door, but once it had been moved aside, the oddest sight greeted their eyes. The descending slope of a passage filled to the brim with little white stone chips. Almost like a Stoney beach, carter thought. But then, where did all these chips come from? They must have been carried here by the flood waters of the Nile.\nHe looked up the staircase. \"We're going to need some help,\" he said to Carvanon.\nAs they cleared the stones, they encountered bits of pottery and seals from burial shrouds that gave the increasing impression that the tomb had been looted in the past. In fact, many of the pieces bore the name 'Tutankhamen'. Some even bore the image of Pharaoh himself. One piece, a small clay vase, caught Callendar's eye. On top of the lid of the vessel was scratched the name of a man named Amenemhet, who would later be known as Akhenamun.\nCallendar handed it to Carter, whose pencil raced over the page. As if reading off a list, he wrote, 'Hatshepsut', 'Nefertiti' and 'Akhnaten.' \n\"After clearing 9 metres of the descending passage, in about\nthe middle of the afternoon, we came upon a second sealed\ndoorway, which was almost the exact replica of the first. It\nbore similar seal impressions and had similar traces of\nsuccessive re-openings and re-closings in the plastering.\nThe seal impressions were of Tût-ankh-Amen and of the Royal\nNecropolis, but not in any way so clear as those on the\nfirst doorway. The entrance and passage both in plan and in\nstyle resembled almost to measurement the tomb containing\nthe cache of Akhenaten discovered by Davis in the very near\nvicinity; which seemed to substantiate our first conjecture\nthat we had found a cache. \nFeverishly we cleared away the remaining last scraps\nof rubbish on the floor of the passage before the doorway until\nwe had only the clean sealed doorway before us. In which,\nafter making preliminary notes, we made a tiny breach in the top\nleft-hand corner to see what was beyond. Darkness and the iron testing\nrod told us that there was empty space. Perhaps another descending\nstaircase, in accordance with the ordinary royal Theban tomb plan?\nOr maybe a chamber? Candles were procured - the all-important Tell-Tale for foul gases when opening \nan ancient subterranean excavation - \nOn 19 March 1923, Carnarvon suffered a severe mosquito bite which became infected by a razor cut. On 5 April, he died in the Continental-Savoy Hotel in Cairo, caused, according to contemporaneous reports, by blood poisoning progressing to pneumonia. On 14 April, Lady Almina Carnarvon moved Lord Carnarvon's remains to England. His tomb appropriately reflects his archaeological interest, nestled within an ancient hill fort overlooking his family seat at Beacon Hill, Burghclere, Hampshire. Carnarvon was survived by his wife Almina, who subsequently remarried, and their two children.\n***\nThe air was full of the dusty substance that had surrounded those white stones, and it was difficult to breathe. Carter was filthy, and the group was exhausted. Carter widened the breach in the stone doorway with his chisel, leaning close to the doorway. It was too dark. He held the candle up and peered past the flickering flame. Lady Carvanon, Lady Evelyn, Arthur Callender, all waiting with bated breath. It took Carter almost a minute for his eyes to adjust to the low light. \"It was sometime before one could see; the hot air escaping caused the candle to flicker, but as soon as one's eyes became accustomed to the glimmer of light the interior of the chamber gradually loomed before one, with its strange and wonderful medley of extraordinary and beautiful objects heaped upon one another. There was naturally short suspense for those present who could not see when Lord Carnarvon said to me 'Can you see anything?'. I replied to him. Yes, it is wonderful.\"\n***\nChapter Nine - The Antechamber of a King\nMace would later recall the unusual group of people that gathered to see the Tomb of Tut. The Allenbys, the Queen of the Belgians, and Prince Leopold were seated opposite the Macy's Lady Evelyn, The Maudseleys, Thomases, Miss Putnam, the Thompsons, Hetheringtons, Doctors Breasted, Capart, Allan, Gardiner, and the Davies, Mertons, and the like were all scattered about in the dining space. They were gathered for the viewing of a king. The Queen would prove to be an annoyance to the passionate Carter in her persistent visits over the coming months, while her companion was content to smoke and conversate with the locals while she gawked at the underworld. \n***",
